[start section id="20102"]

Follow-up of rectal cancer.

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

I saw Mr. Buck in follow-up, a delightful 52-year-old male from New York North Versailles, who presented with a T3, N1 rectal cancer and received preoperative radiation therapy concurrently with 5-FU and oxaliplatin as per a clinical trial.  There was minimal residual submucosal disease in the surgical specimen, and no evidence of metastasis in any of the resected lymph nodes.  The patient underwent a LAR with a temporary colostomy.
Mr. Buck is recovering from surgery without complications at this point, although he required a long hospitalization, almost two-weeks, due to a slow return of bowel function.  He is having some problems with the adhesive tape in the colostomy.  He has chosen to use masking tape applied to the skin, and this is causing irritation of the area where the tape is applied.
The patient developed mild numbness and tingling in the tip of fingers and toes made worse by cold weather while receiving oxaliplatin, but this has resolved.
The medications for the most are unremarkable.

[end section id="20103"]

